# Documentation Guidelines

## API Documentation

- Use OpenAPI 3.0 specification for API documentation
- Generate documentation from code annotations
- Place OpenAPI specification in `/openapi` directory
- Make documentation available at `/docs` endpoint
- Update documentation for every API change
- Include request/response examples for all endpoints

## Code Documentation

- Document all public methods and classes
- Use YARD or RDoc for code documentation
- Include usage examples for complex methods
- Keep documentation up-to-date with code changes
- Document edge cases and error handling

## README and Project Documentation

- Maintain a comprehensive README.md
- Include setup instructions for development
- Document environment variables and configuration
- Provide troubleshooting guidance
- Include links to API documentation

## Authentication Documentation

- Document all authentication methods (JWT, Basic Auth, API Key)
- Provide clear examples for each authentication method
- Document rate limits and authorization requirements
- Include security best practices for API consumers

## Specification Generation

- Infer OpenAPI specification from models, controllers, and routes
- Use annotations to enhance the specification
- Validate the specification against standards
- Test documentation for correctness and completeness
- Ensure all endpoints are documented

## Documentation UI

- Provide a user-friendly documentation UI
- Use ReDoc or Swagger UI for interactive documentation
- Ensure documentation is responsive and accessible
- Allow testing API calls from the documentation UI 